^B@2^r@3^*BMarti Ronemus: ^*N|cp||at|Today, I'm going to share with you three of the most important lessons in bridge you will ever learn.|
pg| ***** 148 ***** |


AT|

Lesson ##1. Bridge is a game of TRICKS, not points. We work so hard to memorize what bids we are allowed to make with what point count. We use our fingers, our toes, our nose, but often we forget that there is so much more to a hand than the points. PLUS! We tend to forget that we're only seeing half of our hand, anyway. The other half is sitting across the table. Next hand is the perfect example of this lesson. Between Pard and us, we've only got 24 HCP (High Card Points) but we're going to bid (and make) a grand slam.|
pg| ***** 149 ***** |


AT|

Lesson ##2. No five-card suit in dummy should ever be ignored. Repeat at least twice. When you find yourself in terrible trouble with little hope of salvation, don't give up if there's a five-card suit in dummy, no matter how moth-eaten it is. If you master and memorize this tip, you'll often get yourself out of trouble – when you don't deserve it. Again, today's hand is a great example. We will use our pathetic five-card dummy suit and prevail.|
pg| ***** 150 ***** |


AT|

Lesson ##3. The crazier your Pard is acting/bidding, the nicer you have to be to him/her. Why? When you run over him in the parking lot and the police arrive, everyone will say, "Oh, his Pard couldn't have done it on purpose! They were getting along so well." It will go down as an accident, rather than the pre-meditated murder it was. Again, today's hand shows the wisdom of this. No thanks to Pard, we're going to make this contract, one way or another.|
